CV-19 Grantmaking strategic planning analytics

Burlington County, New Jersey
An atlas of COVID-19 era need and philanthropic response

July 2020


This report provides strategic planning intelligence to philanthropies making placed-based investments in the wake of COVID-19. The goal is to understand where the supply of resources are aligned with the demand for those resources, and where they are not. Philanthropies can then use this intelligence to plan future investments.

This report is part of a larger effort to chronicle philanthropic efforts to battle COVID-19 in the Delaware Valley Region.

Organizations in Burlington County, New Jersey applied for 1 grants. These grants totalled $3,000.

The organizational mission that saw the most funding in Burlington County, was Human Services, which received $3,000. 1% of Burlington County Census tracts were awarded funding.

The next section provides additional grantmaking analytics.1 Section 2 visualizes a series of strategic planning overlay maps intended to help philanthropies working in Burlington County identify areas where need currently outweighs grant resources. The remaining sections include additional analytics. Worth noting is the Employment section, which visualizes the geography of COVID-related unemployment.

2. Strategic Planning Overlays

The goal of these map overlays is to help stakeholders understand if resources are being allocated where they are needed most. Philanthropies should consider targeting future investment in places where need exceeds grantmaking.

Housing instability and social vulnerability indices define the geography of need in Burlington County. Housing instability is a composite that describes the number of renters, the number of renters paying more than 30% of their income on rent (ie. ‘rent burdened’), and the current tract-level unemployment rate.2

Social vulnerability is a composite of rent burdened households, single-parent households, tract-level poverty rate, percent receiving SNAP benefits, and percent without health insurance. Below, need and grantmaking are visualized side-by-side and with cartographic overlays. Again, these overlays highlight areas where more investment may be needed.

These are relative measures for Burlington County only, which received $3,000 across 1 grants. The grants visualized below have been georeferenced to the service area.

2.1 Housing instability & grantmaking maps

2.2 Housing instability & grantmaking overlay

Census tracts visualized in darker blue, are those where relative housing instability is greater than relative grantmaking. Shades of white are those where housing instability and grantmaking are properly aligned. Darker shades of red are tracts where there is more grantmaking than relative instability.

2.3 Social vulnerability & grantmaking maps

2.4 Social vulnerability & grantmaking overlay

Again, Census tracts visualized in darker blue, are those where relative social vulnerability is greater than relative grantmaking. Shades of white are those where social vulnerability and grantmaking are properly aligned. Darker shades of red are tracts where there is more relative grantmaking than relative instability.

3. Housing

With respect to housing in Burlington County, New Jersey, the average tract-level median rent is $1,250.01. The average rate of owner occupied housing is 74%. In 45% of tracts, at least half of households are rent burdened.

The maps below provide a detailed look at housing in Burlington County.

4. Demographics

In Burlington County, New Jersey, the average median household income is $87,305.28 and the average population density is 2,497 people per square mile. The mean poverty rate is 7%, with the highest poverty rate, areawide, being 32%.

5. Employment

In this section, labor force participation is visualized along with recent changes that have resulted from COVID-19.

The average rate of individuals who have attained at least a high school degree in Burlington County, New Jersey is 93%. In 2015, the Census estimated that 219,817 individuals were employed, which represents 79% of adults. As of mid May, 2020, the estimated average tract-level unemployment rate was 7% meaning an estimated 13,659 fewer individuals were employed at that time.

The geography of COVID-19 unemployment is explored further below.

6. Food Insecurity

In Burlington County, New Jersey, the average rate of households receiving food assistance is 6%. The average rate of households with children receiving food assistance areawide is 3%.
